<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1914-12-19T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1914-12-19T00:00:00-05:00" n="431" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d431">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 763.72112/576</note>
                            <head>
                                <hi rend="italic">The British Ambassador</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_SRSCA1" type="from"><hi rend="italic">Spring
                                        Rice</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Counselor for the Department of State</gloss>
                                </hi>
                            </head>
                            <dateline>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">British Embassy</hi>, <lb/>
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1914-12-19">
                                    <hi rend="italic">December 19, 1914</hi>.</date>
                                <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received December 21</hi>.] </dateline>
                            <p>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">My dear Mr. Counsellor</hi>: With regard to the
                                definition of the expression “copper unwrought” I have been informed
                                by <persName corresp="#p_GSE1">Sir E. Grey</persName> that the
                                subject is being carefully studied and a decision will be made
                                shortly which will be at once communicated.</p>
                            <p>Yours truly,</p>
                            <closer>
                                <signed>
                                    <persName corresp="#p_SRSCA1">
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Cecil Spring Rice</hi>
                                    </persName>
                                </signed>
                            </closer>
                        </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>